eloped a program in endothelial regeneration using induced pluripotential stem cells to generate endothelial cells for therapy of vascular disease these human ipscs can also be used to generate vascular cells from patients with vascular diseases so as to study pathophysiological mechanisms and explore new therapies last updated november 3 2011 you are here stanford medicine school of medicine departments department of medicine cardiovascular medicine vascular medicine & biology navigation for this section vascular medicine & biology about us clinic research training & fellowship faculty contact home additinal links cardiovascular medicine about us people patient care research education medicine divisions home site navigation about us overview message from the chiefs contact us facilities support us people faculty by specialty faculty by name fellows staff education overview general cardiology fellowship overview educational objectives core curriculum research training policies advanced fellowships cv imaging at stanford research training in myocardial biology application procedure faculty fellows program outline conferences application procedure research overview clinical trials basic science clinical outcomes patient care overview electrophysiology interventional cardiology consultative cardiology lymphedema center vascular medicine & biology home about us clinic research training & fellowship faculty contact atherosclerosis and cardiovascular therapies center for marfan syndrome heart lung transplantation heart failure & cardiomyopathy imaging center adult congenital heart disease preventive cardiology medicine divisions department of medicine home biomedical informatics research blood and marrow transplantation cardiovascular medicine endocrinology gastroenterology general medical disciplines formerly general internal medicine and family & community medicine hematology immunology and rheumatology infectious diseases nephrology oncology primary care and outcomes r